#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <unistd.h>

#define TOTAL_FRAMES 5

int main() {
    int i = 1; // Current frame to send
    int timer = 0;
    int outcome; // 0 = Loss, 1 = Ack, 2 = Timeout

    printf("--- SIMULATING STOP AND WAIT ARQ ---\n\n");

    while (i <= TOTAL_FRAMES) {
        printf("SENDER: Sending Frame %d...\n", i);
        
        // Simulation: "Sending" takes a bit of time
        sleep(1); 

        // RANDOM EVENT GENERATOR
        // We simulate 3 scenarios:
        // 0-4: Successful ACK
        // 5-7: Packet Lost (Timeout)
        // 8-9: ACK Lost (Timeout)
        int luck = rand() % 10; 

        if (luck < 5) {
            // Scenario 1: Success
            printf("RECEIVER: Frame %d received correctly.\n", i);
            printf("RECEIVER: Sending ACK %d.\n", i + 1);
            printf("SENDER: ACK %d received. Moving to next frame.\n\n", i + 1);
            i++; // Move to next frame
        } 
        else if (luck < 8) {
            // Scenario 2: Frame Lost
            printf("NETWORK: Frame %d DROPPED in transit!\n", i);
            printf("SENDER: Timer expired (Timeout). Resending Frame %d...\n\n", i);
            // 'i' does not increase, so loop repeats same frame
        } 
        else {
            // Scenario 3: ACK Lost (Tricky case!)
            printf("RECEIVER: Frame %d received correctly.\n", i);
            printf("RECEIVER: Sending ACK %d.\n", i + 1);
            printf("NETWORK: ACK %d DROPPED in transit!\n", i + 1);
            printf("SENDER: Timer expired. Resending Frame %d...\n", i);
            printf("RECEIVER: Duplicate Frame %d detected! Discarding but re-sending ACK.\n\n", i);
            // In a real protocol, we handle duplicate detection here. 
            // For simplicity, we just resend.
        }
    }

    printf("--- All %d Frames Sent Successfully ---\n", TOTAL_FRAMES);
    return 0;
}

Part 3: Lab Record (Algo & Output)
Experiment 5a: Simulation of Stop and Wait ARQ Protocol

Aim: To simulate the Stop and Wait Flow Control protocol and demonstrate how it handles packet loss and acknowledgement.

Algorithm
Start.

Initialize the total number of frames to send (N).

Set the current frame counter i = 1.

Loop while i <= N:

Send: Sender transmits Frame i. Start Timer.

Decision (Simulated): Generate a random number to determine channel status.

Case 1 (Success): If channel is clear:

Receiver accepts Frame i.

Receiver sends ACK i+1.

Sender receives ACK, increments i.

Case 2 (Packet Loss): If random number indicates loss:

Frame i never reaches Receiver.

Sender waits for Timer to expire (Timeout).

Sender retransmits Frame i.

Case 3 (ACK Loss): If ACK i+1 is lost:

Sender waits for Timer to expire.

Sender retransmits Frame i.

Receiver detects duplicate, discards frame, and resends ACK i+1.

End Loop when all frames are acknowledged.

Stop.
